<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880322-0145 </DOCNO><HL> Corrections andamp; Amplifications: Robert Gates </HL><SO> </SO><CO> GOVMT FREST </CO><IN> MON ELE </IN><G> CNG EXE </G><TEXT>   ROBERT GATES, deputy director of the Central Intelligence Agency, wrote in a recent Foreign Affairs article that the &quot;CIA today finds itself in a remarkable position, involuntarily poised nearly equidistant between the executive and legislative branches.&quot; He also wrote that &quot;there is sometimes a strong impulse on the part of intelligence officers to show that a policy decision is misguided or wrong, to poke an analytical finger in the policy eye,&quot; and that &quot;to protect the independence of the analyst while keeping such impulses in check is one of the toughest jobs of intelligence agency managers.&quot; In a previous edition, Mr. Gates's position was misstated.    (See: &quot;Tampering by CIA With Toshiba Affair Gets It Into Trouble With Policy Makers&quot; -- WSJ March 21, 1988)</TEXT></DOC>